SECTION 1 — Energy Flow in Ecosystems
The engine that drives all life
1.1 What is Energy Flow?
Energy flow is the transfer of energy through the biotic components of an ecosystem via feeding
relationships. It is unidirectional (one-way) and non-cyclic — unlike matter, energy cannot be recycled
within the ecosystem. Once energy is lost as heat, it cannot be reused.
Key Principle: Energy enters ecosystems as solar radiation, is fixed by producers through
photosynthesis, flows through consumers, and is ultimately lost as heat. Matter cycles; energy
flows.
