SECTION 2 — Laws of Thermodynamics in Ecology
Physical laws that govern energy in ecosystems
The flow of energy in ecosystems is governed by the Laws of Thermodynamics. These are universal
physical laws that apply to all energy transformations, including those in living systems.
First Law of
Thermodynamics (Law of
Conservation of Energy)
"Energy can neither be created nor destroyed, only converted from one
form to another." Ecological application: The total energy entering an
ecosystem (solar radiation) equals the energy stored in biomass + energy
lost as heat. When plants photosynthesize: Light energy ® Chemical
energy (glucose). When animals eat: Chemical energy ® Kinetic energy +
Heat + Body growth. The total energy is always conserved — just
changed in form.
Second Law of
Thermodynamics (Law of
Entropy)
"In every energy transformation, some energy is lost as heat (unusable
energy). Entropy (disorder) always increases in a closed system."
Ecological application: This is WHY only ~10% energy transfers
between trophic levels — the rest (90%) is lost as heat during respiration,
movement, and metabolic processes. This is why energy pyramids are
always upright. This is why food chains are short (3-5 levels). Energy
cannot be recycled — it flows in ONE direction only.
n SIMPLE ANALOGY: Imagine 1,000 rupees given to a grasshopper (it eats grass worth 1,000 cal).
The grasshopper spends 900 on "expenses" (heat, movement, excretion) and saves only 100. The
frog that eats the grasshopper gets only 100 cal, spends 90, saves 10. The snake gets only 10 cal
— and so on. This is the 2nd Law in action.
