Fig 2: Major Energy Flow Models in Ecology
Lindeman's Trophic
Dynamics Model (1942)
Raymond Lindeman studied Cedar Bog Lake (Minnesota, USA) and
proposed the 10% Law — only ~10% of energy at any trophic level is passed
to the next level. Published in the journal Ecology (1942) at age 27, shortly
before his death. This was the first quantitative model of energy flow in an
ecosystem. He coined the terms: Eutrophication, trophic level, trophic
efficiency.
Odum's Silver Springs
Model (1957)
Eugene Odum studied Silver Springs, Florida (USA) and created the first
detailed energy budget for an entire ecosystem. He quantified: GPP, NPP,
energy at each trophic level, and heat losses. His work confirmed Lindeman's
10% rule and showed how energy flows through a real ecosystem. Silver
Springs had: GPP=20,810 kcal/m²/yr; NPP=11,977 kcal/m²/yr.
H.T. Odum's Energy
Circuit Language
Howard T. Odum (Eugene's brother) developed a symbolic language to
diagram energy flows in ecosystems. He introduced the concept of EMERGY
(solar Embodied Energy) — converting all energy inputs into solar energy
equivalents to compare systems.
