4.2 Types of Food Chains in Detail
Grazing Food Chain
(GFC)
Starts with LIVING green plants (producers). Energy flows from autotrophs to
herbivores to carnivores. This is the most visible food chain. Examples: •
Terrestrial: Grass ® Grasshopper ® Frog ® Snake ® Eagle • Aquatic:
Phytoplankton ® Zooplankton ® Small fish ® Large fish ® Shark • Pond: Algae
® Water insect ® Small fish ® Crane Dominant in: Aquatic ecosystems,
productive grasslands.
Detritus Food Chain
(DFC)
Starts with DEAD organic matter (detritus). Energy flows from dead
plant/animal material to detritivores and decomposers. Detritus = dead organic
matter (fallen leaves, dead animals, faeces, etc.) Examples: • Forest leaf litter
® Millipede ® Centipede ® Frog ® Snake • Dead wood ® Fungi ® Springtail
® Beetle ® Bird Dominant in: Forest ecosystems (80-90% of energy flows
through DFC!). More efficient than GFC as energy is not wasted fighting
predators.
Page 8 | UGC NET Env. Sciences — Unit 3.4 Ecosystem Functions
Parasitic Food Chain Starts with HOST organism. Energy flows from large host to smaller parasites
(unlike GFC where larger eats smaller). Examples: • Buffalo ® Tick ® Protozoa
(on tick) • Tree ® Bark beetle ® Mite Key feature: In this chain, organisms get
SMALLER at each step (opposite of grazing food chain). The host loses energy
to parasites.
4.3 Characteristics of Food Chains
• Food chains are rarely longer than 4-5 trophic levels due to energy loss (10% rule)
• Arrows always show direction of energy flow (prey ® predator)
• The first organism is always the producer (autotroph) in GFC
• Food chains are interconnected to form food webs in real ecosystems
• Longer food chains = less energy available at top = less biomass at top
• In most forests, DFC > GFC in terms of energy flow
• Omnivores connect multiple trophic levels simultaneously
