SECTION 6 — Biogeochemical Cycles
How matter cycles through ecosystems — unlike energy, matter is recycled
6.1 Introduction
Biogeochemical cycles (BGC) are the pathways by which chemical elements and molecules (nutrients)
move through biotic (bio) and abiotic (geo, chemical) components of the Earth. Unlike energy, matter is
recycled — the same atoms cycle through organisms and the environment repeatedly.
Key distinction from Energy Flow: Energy flows UNIDIRECTIONALLY (Sun ® Producers ®
Consumers ® Heat — lost forever). Matter CYCLES (same atoms used over and over by different
organisms).
6.2 Classification of Biogeochemical Cycles
Gaseous Cycles
(Atmospheric)
The reservoir (main store) is the atmosphere or ocean. These cycles are
FAST and GLOBAL — disturbances recover quickly. Examples: Carbon cycle
(COn reservoir), Nitrogen cycle (Nn reservoir), Oxygen cycle (On reservoir),
Hydrogen cycle (HnO reservoir).
Sedimentary Cycles
(Lithospheric)
The reservoir is the rocks and soil (lithosphere). These cycles are SLOW
and LOCAL — disturbances take millions of years to recover. Examples:
Phosphorus cycle (in rocks), Sulphur cycle (in rocks/soil), Iron cycle, Calcium
cycle.
6.3 Carbon Cycle
Carbon is the backbone of all organic molecules. The carbon cycle describes how carbon moves
between the atmosphere, biosphere, hydrosphere, and lithosphere. Main reservoir: atmosphere (COn)
and oceans (dissolved COn, carbonate).
