SECTION 8 — Phosphorus and Sulphur Cycles
Sedimentary cycles — no atmospheric reservoir
8.1 Phosphorus Cycle
Phosphorus is essential for ATP, DNA, RNA, phospholipids (cell membranes), and bones. Unlike C
and N, phosphorus has NO ATMOSPHERIC RESERVOIR — it moves only between rocks/soil, water, and
organisms. It is a sedimentary cycle — the slowest biogeochemical cycle.
Step What Happens
1. Weathering of
rocks
Phosphate-containing rocks (apatite) weather ® POn³n released to soil/water
2. Plant uptake Plants absorb POn³n from soil; bacteria help solubilise phosphate (e.g., Bacillus
megaterium)
3. Consumer
absorption
Animals get P by eating plants; stored in bones, teeth, cell membranes
4. Decomposition Dead matter decomposed ® POn³n returned to soil
5. Runoff to water Phosphate washed into rivers, lakes, oceans
6. Sedimentation Phosphate settles in ocean sediments ® forms new rock over millions of years
7. Uplift (geological) Rock uplift brings phosphate back to land (very slow — millions of years)
Why Phosphorus is a Limiting Nutrient: In most aquatic ecosystems, phosphorus is the limiting
nutrient (controls primary productivity). When excess P enters water bodies (from fertilisers,
detergents) ® Eutrophication (algal blooms, oxygen depletion, fish kills).
8.2 Sulphur Cycle
Sulphur is essential for amino acids (cysteine, methionine), proteins, vitamins (thiamine), and
enzyme cofactors. Sulphur has BOTH atmospheric (SOn, HnS) and sedimentary (pyrite, gypsum)
reservoirs.
