SECTION 9 — Ecological Succession
How communities change over time — from bare rock to forest
9.1 Definition
Ecological succession is the process of change in the species composition of a community over
time — a directional, predictable sequence of community changes in response to disturbance or the
creation of new habitat. The process continues until a climax community is reached — a stable,
self-sustaining community in equilibrium with the environment.
Who studied it: Frederic Clements (1916) — concept of climax community and monoclimax theory.
Henry Gleason (1926) — individualistic concept. F.E. Clements coined the term "sere" for the entire
successional sequence.
